it. And the key to this preparation is attention, the only state in which the speaker can perceive the doctrine as a cognitive gift. Along the way, Marno illuminates why attention is required in Christian devotion in the first place and uncovers a tradition of battling distraction that spans from ascetic thinkers and Church Fathers to Catholic spiritual exercises and Protestant prayer manuals.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 29. Mai 2023) 0aAttentionxReligious aspectsxChristianity. 0aChristian poetry, EnglishyEarly modern, 1500-1700xHistory and criticism. 0aDeath in literature. 0aPrayer. 7aRELIGION / General.2bisacsh  aEarly Modern.  aEnglish Renaissance.  aJohn Donne.  aattention.  adevotion.  adistraction.  aphenomenology.  apoetry.  aprayer.  aspiritual exercise.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertUniversity of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2016z97831107109840 cprintz978022641597040uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780226416021423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780226416021/original  a978-3-11-071098-4  University of Chicago Press Complete eBook-Package 2016b2016  aEBA_FAO  aGBV-deGruyter-alles